<HEADLINE>
Wild rabbit questions
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<POST>
<POSTER> souleNOSPAM </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 1999-06-07T12:00:00 </POSTDATE>
Email: souleNOS ... @rpa.net
Groups: alt.animals.breeders.rabbits


We have come into the care of a &quot;saved&quot; young wild rabbit. It is the
sole survivor of a litter of appr. 8-9 which were found under a
neighbor's porch and is appr. 4-6 weeks old. We live in a suburban
area where these rabbits are plentiful- indeed, there is an
undeveloped field behind our home where many of them certainly make
their homes.

We are keeping the rabbit in a typical animal cage (with a removable
tray beneath a wire floor) in our airy garage. Temps here range 70s to
90s (F) during the day, as low as low 50s at night.

My questions to the NG are:

1) How old do you suppose the rabbit must be for us to release
it into the field with a reasonably &quot;fighting&quot; chance for survival?

2) What time of day would allow it to meld into the
environment with, perhaps, the least chance of being immediately
attacked? (I was thinking of early evening, but perhaps nighttime
predators might be likely to nab it before it had a chance to find
shelter.)

3) Are rabbits socially accepting of newcomers? That is, do
you suppose the rabbits already living in the field will welcome our
rabbit into their &quot;family?&quot;

Thanks from me and my kids for any advise you might have for us.

Brian

